Art is the process or product of deliberately arranging elements in a way that appeals to the sense or emotions. It encompasses a diverse range of human activities, creations, and modes of expression, including music and literature. The meaning of art is explored in a branch of philosophy known as Aesthetics.

The definition and evaluation of art has become especially problematic since the early 20th century. Richard Wollheim distinguishes three approaches: the Realist, whereby aesthetic quality is an absolute value independent of any human view; the Objectivist, whereby it is also an absolute value, but is dependent on general human experience; and the Relativist position, whereby it is not an absolute value, but depends on, and varies with, the human experience of different humans.[1] An object may be characterized by the intentions, or lack thereof, of its creator, regardless of its apparent purpose. A cup, which ostensibly can be used as a container, may be considered art if intended solely as an ornament, while a painting may be deemed craft if mass-produced.

Traditionally, the term art was used to refer to any skill or mastery. This conception changed during the Romantic period, when art came to be seen as "a special faculty of the human mind to be classified with religion and science".[2] Generally, art is made with the intention of stimulating thoughts and emotions.

The nature of art has been described by

Richard Wollheim

as "one of the most elusive of the traditional problems of human culture".

[3]

It has been defined as a vehicle for the expression or communication of emotions and ideas, a means for exploring and appreciating

formal elements

for their own sake, and as

mimesis

or

representation

.

[4] Leo Tolstoy

identified art as a use of indirect means to communicate from one person to another.

[4] Benedetto Croce

and

R.G. Collingwood

advanced the

idealist

view that art expresses emotions, and that the work of art therefore essentially exists in the mind of the creator.

[5][6]

The theory of art as form has its roots in the philosophy of

Immanuel Kant

, and was developed in the early twentieth century by

Roger Fry

and

Clive Bell

.

[4]

Art as

mimesis

or representation has deep roots in the philosophy of

Aristotle

.

Magnolia 5.2 comes with a range of key improvements: it delivers tools for a smoother migration, makes most modules natively available, introduces a brand-new REST module, and offers more flexibility for role-based security.

The migration road trip continues. The migration tools delivered in 5.2 now include changes between 4.5 and 5.2 such as dialog configuration, replacing the DMS with DAM, and storing metadata in mixin node types. You also get migration documentation, workshops and support.
Most modules are now migrated to native 5 apps using the new Vaadin UI: Shop, RSS Aggregator, Google Sitemap and Google Analytics are in this latest batch of updates.

Magnolia’s new REST module allows you to access Magnolia remotely, for example from another application. It also makes it easy to expose your own REST services, and provides self-documentation of those services.

You can now organize roles, groups and users into folders. Folders let you work in a multitenancy fashion where a department administrator can manage users contained in a department specific folder, for example.
New in 5.2: More flexibility for role-based security

With Magnolia 5, users get a CMS with smartphone simplicity inside. Its beautiful, simple and intuitive interface saves them frustration and effort. Developers get more time to write code when customizing and extending Magnolia due to a strong UI platform that's based on HTML 5 and Vaadin.
